// We are going to simulate an asynchronous function. It will delay its response for 1000ms. 
// Our function merely represents a delay that might be encountered during an API call or a database query.
const asyncAction = () => {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      // After the delay, we will resolve the promise with the 'Hello' string.
      resolve('Hello');
    }, 1000);
  });
};

// Then, we are going to start our promise chain.
(async () => {
  // This self-invoking asynchronous function is called Immediately Invoked Function Expression (IIFE).
  try {
    const message = await asyncAction()
    // We utilize 'await' keyword here to catch the result when promise is resolved, it's available within async function.
    console.log(message);  
  } catch(err) {
    // If error occurs in await, it can be caught with this block. Usually happens when the promise is rejected or some error in async function.
     console.error(err);
  }
})();

// When we run this function, JavaScript will first run the anonymous asynchronous function, and then it goes to the event loop to wait for other tasks. 
// The function asyncAction is called inside IIFE. Despite that it takes 1000ms to resolve, JavaScript won't stop in this function due to the nature of non-blocking I/O model. Instead, it's going to set a timer 
// and once the time is up, the promise will be resolved, and we catch the resolved value with 'await'. Then the string 'Hello' will be printed out in the console.
// If any error occurs within the promise or the asynchronous function, it will be caught with the catch error block and logger in the console.
```

Please note that the anonymous function is asynchronous. It enables us to use the `await` keyword to pause and resume the JavaScript engine's execution within that function allowing us to write asynchronous code in a way that it looks synchronous. 

The try-catch block is very useful to handle any error or rejection in the promise chain. It's a common practice to use it for the promise chain when using async/await syntax. If any error occurs within the async/await function, which will break the execution flow, it will be caught by the catch block, and it's a good place to add error handling logic.

However, using Promise chaining is not the best way to manage asynchronous code in complex systems, as it could lead to callback hell if not handled well. Using more modern approaches such as async/await is advisable. 

