Dynamic memory allocation is a mechanism that enables programs to obtain more memory space during execution. This is done by taking memory from a memory pool known as the heap, to meet the exact memory requirements on the fly. In C++, dynamic memory allocation techniques like unique_ptr and shared_ptr are used for efficient memory management and to ensure destructors are called to clean up memory, reducing memory leaks. 

A unique_ptr is a smart pointer which owns and manages another object through a pointer and destroys that object when the unique_ptr goes out of scope. No two unique_ptrs can manage the same object. 

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

int main(){
   unique_ptr<int> p1(new int(42));
   cout << "p1 points to " << *p1 << '\n';
   // Ownership can be transferred
   unique_ptr<int> p2 = move(p1); 
   cout << "p2 points to " << *p2 << '\n';
   return 0;
}
```

shared_ptr is a smart pointer that retains shared ownership over an object. It can be copied, assigning another shared_ptr with a copy of the controlled object increases the control block’s shared count.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

int main(){
   shared_ptr<int> p1(new int(42));
   cout << "p1 points to " << *p1 << '\n';
   // Ownership can be shared
   shared_ptr<int> p2 = p1;  
   cout << "p2 points to " << *p2 << '\n';
   return 0;
}
```

About the custom memory pool, using it, you can allocate memory for a certain number of objects in advance, which speeds up object creation and destroys command as they do not require direct interaction with the operating system. This can make a significant difference in performance for applications where a large number of objects are created and deleted. 

Here is an example of a custom memory allocator for a simple type like int:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>

struct Allocator{
   using value_type = int;
   Allocator() = default;

   int* allocate( std::size_t n){
      return new int[n];
   }

   void deallocate(int* p, std::size_t){
      delete[] p;
   }
};

int main(){
   std::allocator<Allocator::value_type> a1;  
   int* a = a1.allocate(1);   
   a1.deallocate(a, 1);
