Here is a simple Java program that performs bubble sort on an array of integers. The program prints out each step of the sorting process for educational purposes.

```java
public class BubbleSort {
    void bubbleSort(int arr[]) {
        int n = arr.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
            System.out.println("Step " + (i+1));
            for (int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
                if (arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
                    // swap arr[j+1] and arr[i]
                    int temp = arr[j];
                    arr[j] = arr[j+1];
                    arr[j+1] = temp;
                }
                printArray(arr);
            }
        }
    }

    /* Prints the array */
    void printArray(int arr[]) {
        int n = arr.length;
        for (int i=0; i<n; ++i)
            System.out.print(arr[i] + " ");
        System.out.println();
    }

    // Driver method to test above
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        BubbleSort bs = new BubbleSort();
        int arr[] = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
        System.out.println("Unsorted array");
        bs.printArray(arr);
        bs.bubbleSort(arr);
        System.out.println("Sorted array");
        bs.printArray(arr);
    }
}
```

This program first prints the unsorted array. Then it starts the bubble sort algorithm by comparing each pair of adjacent elements and swapping them if they are in the wrong order. After each swap, it prints the current state of the array. Finally, it prints the sorted array.

To design a peeking iterator that works with any type instead of just integers, we can use a generic approach. We need to make our `PeekingIterator` class generic over the type of elements in our input iterator. To achieve this, let's modify our `PeekingIterator` class and make it generic as follows:

```java
public class PeekingIterator<T> {

    private final Iterator<T> iterator;
    private T nextElement;

    public PeekingIterator(Iterator<T> iterator) {
        this.iterator = iterator;
        this.nextElement = iterator.hasNext() ? iterator.next() : null;
    }

    public T next() {
        T current = nextElement;
        nextElement = (iterator.hasNext() ? iterator.next() : null);
        return current;
    }

    public T peek() {
        return nextElement;
    }

    public boolean hasNext() {
        return nextElement != null || iterator.hasNext();
    }
}
```

Now, this `PeekingIterator` class can work with any type of elements and will maintain the state of the peek element in addition to the iterator's state. To test our peeking iterator, we can do the following:

```java
PeekingIterator<Integer> peekingIntegerIterator = new PeekingIterator<>(Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3).iterator());
peekingIntegerIterator.next(); // 1
peekingIntegerIterator.peek(); // 2
peekingIntegerIterator.next(); // 2
peekingIntegerIterator.next(); // 3
peekingIntegerIterator.hasNext(); // false

PeekingIterator<String> peekingStringIterator = new PeekingIterator<>(Arrays.asList("apple", "banana", "cherry").iterator());
peekingStringIterator.next(); // apple
peekingStringIterator.peek(); // banana
```

This makes our peeking iterator much more flexible and can be used with types other than integers.

```python
import heapq

class MedianFinder:
    def __init__(self):
        self.left = []  # max heap
        self.right = []  # min heap

    def addNum(self, num: int) -> None:
        if not self.left or num <= -self.left[0]:
            heapq.heappush(self.left, -num)
        else:
            heapq.heappush(self.right, num)

        if len(self.left) < len(self.right):
            heapq.heappush(self.left, -heapq.heappop(self.right))
        elif len(self.left) > len(self.right) + 1:
            heapq.heappush(self.right, -heapq.heappop(self.left))

    def findMedian(self) -> float:
        if len(self.left) == len(self.right):
            return (-self.left[0] + self.right[0]) / 2
        else:
            return -self.left[0]
```

explanation
The algorithm for solving the median in a list of integers works by maintaining two heaps, a max-heap for the left half and a min-heap for the right half. When a new number is added, it is compared to the max value of the left max-heap. If the number is smaller or equal, it is added to the left heap. If the number is larger, it is added to the right min-heap. Then, we balance the two heaps by ensuring that their sizes never differ by more than one. This ensures that the median is always easily accessible as either the largest value in the left heap or the average of the largest value in the left heap and the smallest value in the right heap. The algorithm has an O(log N) time complexity, where N is the number of elements in the list.

