#include <vector>

bool endsWithIgnoreCase(const std::string& str, const std::string& suffix) {
    const size_t n1 = str.length();
    const size_t n2 = suffix.length();
    if (n1 < n2)
        return false;
    return std::equal(str.begin() + (n1 - n2), str.end(), suffix.begin(),
        [](char c1, char c2) {
            return std::tolower(static_cast<unsigned char>(c1))
                == std::tolower(static_cast<unsigned char>(c2));
    });
}

bool filenameHasExtension(const std::string& filename,
                          const std::vector<std::string>& extensions) {
    return std::any_of(extensions.begin(), extensions.end(),
        [&filename](const std::string& extension) {
            return endsWithIgnoreCase(filename, "." + extension);
    });
}

void test(const std::string& filename,
          const std::vector<std::string>& extensions) {
    std::cout << std::setw(20) << std::left << filename
        << ": " << std::boolalpha
        << filenameHasExtension(filename, extensions) << '\n';
}

int main() {
    const std::vector<std::string> extensions{"zip", "rar", "7z",
        "gz", "archive", "A##", "tar.bz2"};
    test("MyData.a##", extensions);
    test("MyData.tar.Gz", extensions);
    test("MyData.gzip", extensions);
    test("MyData.7z.backup", extensions);
    test("MyData...", extensions);
    test("MyData", extensions);
    test("MyData_v1.0.tar.bz2", extensions);
    test("MyData_v1.0.bz2", extensions);
    return 0;
}

Namespaces in C# represent a namespace in the .NET Framework that consists of a set of classes. They are designed to help categorize and manage large codebases, grouping similar tasks, classes, or data types. They are similar to packages in other programming languages such as Java. Namespaces help to prevent name collision (identical names) by grouping the classes that work together. By doing so, they avoid the confusion between identical names that may belong to separate projects.

Nested Namespaces:

Namespaces can be nested within other namespaces, creating a hierarchy. Here is an example:

```csharp
namespace Namespace1 
{
    class Class1 { }
    namespace NestedNamespace 
    {
        class Class2 { }
    }
}
```

The '.' operator is used to access the NestedNamespace and Class2 can be described as `Namespace1.NestedNamespace.Class2`.

Using Keyword:

The `using` keyword in C# is used to include namespaces in a program. A program can use multiple namespaces by defining them at the beginning of the program.

```csharp
using System;
using Namespace1;
```

Best Practices for Namespaces:

1. Namespaces should have a unique name and relevant to the task performed by its classes.
2. Namespace names should follow the company's product division hierarchy.
3. Keep namespaces as simple as possible. It shouldn’t be too deep, too complex, or unnecessary lengthy.

Access Modifiers:

In C#, access modifiers do not apply to namespaces. Classes and methods within a namespace can have access modifiers.

Namespace Collision:

If there is a namespace collision, you would need to use fully qualified names. This means specifying the entire namespace path.

```csharp
namespace MyNameSpace
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            System.Console.WriteLine("Hello, World!"); // Use of fully qualified name
            Console.WriteLine("Hello, again!");
        }
    }
}
```

Name collisions can also be resolved using the `alias` qualifier :

```csharp
using win = Microsoft.Win32;
```

This will help in reducing the error of namespace collision by distinguishing between similar ones. 

However, be aware that even though these methods can be used to resolve naming conflicts, it is better practice to avoid such situation altogether by using appropriate, unique and meaningful namespace names.

To update a single item in a FlatList without re-rendering the entire list, you should use the following approach:

1. Ensure each item in the FlatList has a unique key. This can be done by providing the `keyExtractor` prop to the FlatList.
2. Create a state to hold the data source for the FlatList.
3. Use `React.memo` to optimize the rendering of each list item component. This ensures that the item will only be re-rendered if its props have changed.
4. To update a specific item, modify the data source in your state, making sure to create a new array (by spreading the original array) to trigger the necessary update.

Here's an example:
```javascript
import React, { useState, useCallback } from 'react';
import { FlatList, TouchableOpacity, Text, View } from 'react-native';

const ListItem = React.memo(({ item, onPress }) => {
  return (
    <TouchableOpacity onPress={onPress}>
      <View>
        <Text>{item.title}</Text>
      </View>
    </TouchableOpacity>
  );
});

const App = () => {
  const [data, setData] = useState([
    { id: '1', title: 'Item 1' },
    { id: '2', title: 'Item 2' },
    // ...
  ]);

  const handlePress = useCallback((itemId) => {
    setData((prevData) =>
      prevData.map((item) =>
        item.id === itemId ? { ...item, title: 'Updated Title' } : item
      )
    );
  }, []);

  const renderItem = ({ item }) => (
    <ListItem item={item} onPress={() => handlePress(item.id)} />
  );

  return (
    <FlatList
      data={data}
      renderItem={renderItem}
      keyExtractor={(item) => item.id}
    />
  );
};

export default App;
```
In this example, `ListItem` is wrapped with `React.memo` to optimize rendering, and the `handlePress` function is used to update the specific item in the list. Only the modified item will be re-rendered, while the rest of the list will remain unchanged.

Here's an example of a simple Ethereum smart contract for a community called "BharatBots". This contract uses Solidity programming language and is based on ERC20 standards. Please note that this is a basic example, and you might need to make modifications and optimizations according to your requirements.
```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.8.0;

import "@openzeppelin/contracts/token/ERC20/ERC20.sol";
import "@openzeppelin/contracts/access/Ownable.sol";

contract BharatBots is ERC20, Ownable {
    uint256 private constant INITIAL_SUPPLY = 1000000 * (10 ** uint256(decimals()));
    uint256 public constant JOIN_FEE = 100 * (10 ** uint256(decimals()));

    mapping(address => bool) private _members;

    event MemberJoined(address indexed member);
    event MemberLeft(address indexed member);

    constructor() ERC20("BharatBots", "BBT") {
        _mint(msg.sender, INITIAL_SUPPLY);
    }

    function joinCommunity() public payable {
        require(!_members[msg.sender], "Already a member");
        require(balanceOf(msg.sender) >= JOIN_FEE, "Insufficient BBT tokens to join");

        _transfer(msg.sender, address(this), JOIN_FEE);
        _members[msg.sender] = true;
        emit MemberJoined(msg.sender);
    }

    function leaveCommunity() public {
        require(_members[msg.sender], "Not a member");

        _members[msg.sender] = false;
        emit MemberLeft(msg.sender);
    }

    function isMember(address account) public view returns (bool) {
        return _members[account];
    }

    function adminTransfer(address to, uint256 amount) public onlyOwner {
        _transfer(address(this), to, amount);
    }

    function adminWithdrawEther() public onlyOwner {
        payable(owner()).transfer(address(this).balance);
    }
}
```
This contract extends the ERC20 token standard, using OpenZeppelin's library, and adds the functionality for joining and leaving the community. The contract is owned by an admin, who has root control over it, thanks to the `Ownable` contract from OpenZeppelin.

When an individual wants to join the community, they must have a sufficient number of BharatBots (BBT) tokens in their account to pay the joining fee. The tokens are then transferred to the contract's address. Members can leave the community at any time, and their membership status is tracked in the `_members` mapping.

The admin can transfer tokens from the contract's address and withdraw Ether collected as joining fees using the `adminTransfer` and `adminWithdrawEther` functions, respectively.

