Here's a C# function to compute Fibonacci numbers:
```csharp
using System;

public static class Fibonacci
{
    public static long FibonacciNumber(int n)
    {
        if (n == 0 || n == 1)
        {
            return n;
        }

        long fibBefore = 0;
        long fibCurrent = 1;
        long fibResult = 1;

        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++)
        {
            fibResult = fibBefore + fibCurrent;
            fibBefore = fibCurrent;
            fibCurrent = fibResult;
        }

        return fibResult;
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int n = 10; // change this value to compute Fibonacci number at a desired index
        long fibNumber = Fibonacci.FibonacciNumber(n);
        Console.WriteLine($"The {n}th Fibonacci number is: {fibNumber}");
    }
}
```
This function calculates the nth Fibonacci number in an iterative manner, reducing the computation to O(n) instead of the exponential O(2^n) of recursive solutions. The function starts with the first two Fibonacci numbers, 0 and 1, then iteratively computes the next number by adding the previous two.

Here is an example of how you can create a schema for storing DNS data in Dgraph, with appropriate entities, fields, and relationships:

```graphql
type Domain {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  nsRecords: [Nameserver] @hasMany(livestamp: true, environmentalParameter: "DNS_NAMESERVER_CACHE_TTL")
  aRecords: [ARecord] @hasMany(livestamp: true, environmentalParameter: "DNS_AR_CACHE_TTL")
  createdAt: DateTime!
  updatedAt: DateTime!
}

type Nameserver {
  id: ID!
  ipAddress: String!
  domain: Domain @belongsTo
  createdAt: DateTime!
  updatedAt: DateTime!
}

type ARecord {
  id: ID!
  ipAddress: String!
  domain: Domain @belongsTo
  hostname: String
  createdAt: DateTime!
  updatedAt: DateTime!
}

input CreateDomainInput {
  name: String!
}

input CreateNameserverInput {
  ipAddress: String!
  domainId: ID!
}

input CreateARecordInput {
  ipAddress: String!
  domainId: ID!
  hostname: String
}

schema {
  query: Query
  mutation: Mutation
}

input Mutation {
  createDomain(input: CreateDomainInput!): Domain
  createNameserver(input: CreateNameserverInput!): Nameserver
  createARecord(input: CreateARecordInput!): ARecord
}
```

In this schema, we have three types: `Domain`, `Nameserver`, and `ARecord`. The `Domain` type represents a domain, which has a `name` field, `nsRecords` which are connected to `Nameserver` instances and `aRecords` which are connected to `ARecord` instances via one-to-many relationships.

The `Nameserver` type represents a nameserver instance. It has an `ipAddress` field and a `domain` field referencing the `Domain` it belongs to. This relationship is defined with `belongsTo` constraint and therefore is a one-to-one relationship.

Similarly, the `ARecord` type represents an A record of the domain. It has an `ipAddress`, `hostname` field, and a `domain` field referencing the `Domain` it belongs to. Again, the `belongsTo` constraint implies a one-to-one relationship with `Domain`.

The input types `CreateDomainInput`, `CreateNameserverInput`, and `CreateARecordInput` provide the necessary fields to create instances of respective types in a mutation operation.

By using GraphQL and Dgraph here, you can easily query, filter, and modify the DNS data stored in the schema.

