Does C++ support assignments such as this one?

int i,j;
pair<int, int> t = {3, 5};
i, j = t; // possible in C++?

answer:
There is no direct way to achieve this type of assignment using C++ syntax `i, j = t;`. It would be equivalent to `{i, j} = t;`. However, the correct way to assign elements of a pair to separate variables is to use individual assignment statements:

```c++
int i, j;
pair<int, int> t = {3, 5};
i = t.first;  // assigns 3 to i
j = t.second; // assigns 5 to j
```

Alternatively, you can use object-initialization syntax:

```c++
int i, j;
auto [i_value, j_value] = t; // this is only available in C++17 or later
i = i_value;
j = j_value;
```

This style of initialization is known as "named variable initialization." [source: cppreference](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/user_literals)

Furthermore, this syntax works for initializing variables from other pairs too. However, for older standards and compilers, it is not possible.

```c++
pair<int, int> t1 {1, 2};
auto [x, y] = t1;
// with C++17 onwards.
// x = 1;
// y = 2;
``` 

